What is Load Balancing
Load balancing is the process of intelligently distributing incoming traffic across multiple servers so that:

No server gets overloaded
Requests are handled faster
The system stays available even if some servers fail

Think of it as a traffic manager for your backend systems.

Core Architecture
4 Components:
Client → User request (browser/mobile app)
Load Balancer → Decision maker
Backend Servers → Handle actual processing
Flow:
Client → Load Balancer → Selected Server → Response → Client

 Types of Load Balancers
1. Layer 4 (Transport Level)
Works on IP + Port
Faster (less processing)
Doesn’t inspect request content

Example: TCP load balancing

2. Layer 7 (Application Level)
Works on HTTP/HTTPS
Can inspect:
URL path (/login, /payments)
Headers
Cookies

 Example:

/api/users → Server A
/api/payments → Server B

Load Balancing Strategies (Very Important)
1. Round Robin
Req1 → Server A
Req2 → Server B
Req3 → Server C
Req4 → Server A

Simple
Doesn’t consider server load

2. Weighted Round Robin
Assign weight based on server capacity
Server A (weight 3)
Server B (weight 1)

Traffic → A, A, A, B, A, A, A, B...
Useful when servers are not equal

3. Least Connections
Send request to server with fewest active connections

Great for real-time systems
Handles uneven load well

4. Least Response Time
Chooses server with:
Lowest response time
Least active requests

Optimized for performance

5. IP Hash (Session Affinity)
Same user → same server

Useful for:
Login sessions
Shopping carts

Can cause uneven load

6. Random (with optimization)
Random selection + fallback logic

Surprisingly effective at scale

Failover & High Availability
If one server crashes:
→ Traffic shifts to others automatically

This is critical for production systems

Horizontal Scaling
Add more servers when traffic increases
10k users → 2 servers  
100k users → 10 servers  

Load balancer makes this seamless

Real-World Examples
1. Netflix
Uses load balancing across thousands of servers globally
Routes users to nearest region

2. Amazon (AWS ELB)
Provides managed load balancers
Auto scales based on traffic

3. Google
Uses global load balancing
Routes traffic across continents
Common Tools & Technologies
NGINX → Most popular reverse proxy
HAProxy → High performance
Apache HTTP Server → Basic load balancing

Common Problems & Pitfalls
Single point of failure (if only 1 load balancer)
Uneven traffic distribution
Sticky sessions causing imbalance
Latency due to poor routing

Solution:
Use multiple load balancers + DNS balancing


